Substitute the values directly into the formula $$Q = mc\Delta T$$ to calculate the energy:

$$\begin{aligned} Q &= 2.00 \times 900 \times 10.0 \\ Q &= 18000\ \text{J} 
\end{aligned}$$

First, calculate the combined heat capacity of the cold components (aluminium and water). 

$$\begin{aligned} C_{\text{cold}} &= (m_{\text{Al}} c_{\text{Al}}) + (m_{\text{water}} c_{\text{water}}) \\ C_{\text{cold}} &= (1.50 \times 900) + (2.00 \times 4200) \\ C_{\text{cold}} &= 1350 + 8400 \\ C_{\text{cold}} &= 9750\ \text{J K}^{-1} 
\end{aligned}$$
